People often think: â€œWait! I modified arr[0] and it changed the original â€” so it must be pass-by-reference!â€

But here's the key difference:

ğŸ§  Java Pass-by-Value of Reference â€” How it Works
When you pass an object (like an array or class), Java copies the reference variable (not the actual object).

Both caller and callee now have two separate references pointing to the same object.

If the callee reassigns the reference (e.g., arr = new int[5];), the caller's reference is unaffected.

So you can modify the contents of the object, but you canâ€™t change what the caller's variable points to.

âš ï¸ Java does not allow:
Passing variables by reference like in C++ using &.

Changing the caller's actual variable or reference.

ğŸ›‘ Why Java doesnâ€™t support true pass-by-reference:
Simplicity and safety: Java avoids raw pointers and references to avoid bugs, memory corruption, and undefined behavior common in C/C++.

Garbage Collection: Javaâ€™s memory model depends on predictable reference behavior â€” pass-by-reference would complicate tracking object ownership.

Design choice: Java was designed to be simple, safe, and avoid pitfalls of C++ â€” so it gives you one consistent rule: everything is passed by value, including references.

ğŸ” Analogy:
Language	Can you reassign caller's variable in callee?	Can you mutate contents of object?
Java	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
C++ Ref	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes

