    arr = vector<int>{1, 2};  // replaces caller's vector
}
ğŸ”‘ Why does this replace the original?
vector<int>& arr is a true reference.

Itâ€™s not a copy, it's an alias to the exact same variable in the caller.

So doing arr = ... doesnâ€™t create a new local variable.

It means: â€œupdate the original variable to hold this new vector.â€

âœ… Result: The callerâ€™s arr is updated.

ğŸ§± How C++ Does This Internally
C++ references (&) are just compiler-supported aliases.

The compiler treats arr as a direct name for the original variable.

No new memory is allocated for arr; itâ€™s just another name for the same thing.

â˜• Now: What happens in Java?
java
Copy
Edit
