    arr = new int[]{1, 2};  // does NOT affect caller
}
ğŸ”‘ Why doesnâ€™t this replace the original?
In Java, arr is a copy of the reference.

That means Java creates a new local variable arr in the method.

That local arr points to the same object as the caller â€” initially.

But when you say arr = new int[]{1, 2}, now this local reference points to a new object.

The callerâ€™s reference still points to the old object.

âŒ Result: Callerâ€™s variable is unaffected.

ğŸ§  So, what did the language creators decide differently?
Concept	C++	Java
References (&)	True reference (alias)	Not supported
Function arguments	You can pass by reference or value	Always pass-by-value (including references)
Can reassign callerâ€™s variable	âœ… Yes, with reference	âŒ No
Can mutate the object	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes (via reference copy)
Memory model	Manual / deterministic	Managed by garbage collector

ğŸ› ï¸ Language Design Intent
Java creators (James Gosling, etc.) said:
Java does not have C++-style references because it adds complexity and makes behavior harder to reason about, especially with memory management and garbage collection.

They wanted:

Simplicity â€” only one way to pass parameters.

Safety â€” avoid bugs from aliasing, pointer errors.

GC-friendly semantics â€” everything lives on the heap, references are easily trackable.

C++ creators (Bjarne Stroustrup) gave:
Control â€” let you choose pass-by-value or pass-by-reference.

Performance â€” avoid copies for large objects.

Power â€” you can do nearly anything, even dangerous things.

